        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8784.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Robert Smith, 24 February 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Smith was preparing to read a paper in favour of Darwinism to the Belfast Naturalists’ Field Club (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8784.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Robert Smith, 24 February 1873</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_43.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Louis Agassiz</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2626.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Rudolf Albert von Kölliker</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD had responded to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3473.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Carl Wilhelm von Nägeli’s</ref> views in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6018.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 5th ed.</ref>, pp. 150–7.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2048.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst Haeckel</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_955.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Carl Friedrich Claus</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f8"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_999.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ferdinand Julius Cohn</ref>, in his lecture on the development of science in the last twenty-five years (Cohn 1872, pp. 20–3), had identified <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> as the seminal work of the period, and argued that CD’s theory of natural selection had shed new light on the development of all life.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f9"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_813.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alphonse de Candolle</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_931.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edouard Claparède</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f10">CD probably refers to the first part of Saporta’s study of Tertiary flora in gypsum beds near Aix (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6891.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Saporta 1872–4</ref>). CD’s annotated copy is in the Darwin Pamphlet Collection–CUL.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f11">CD had discussed the views of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1066.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Drinker Cope</ref> in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 6th ed.</ref>, p. 149.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f12">Carl Gegenbaur.</note>
        </div>        
            
